surveyed who had an RTA did not know what compensation they should have received. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">suggests the importance that the role of independent legal advice in securing appropriate compensation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> can play</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The insurance industry and its related counter-parts need to have the use of data capture reviewed and a stronger governance of the use of suc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h data. On the one hand we have insurers who state to government that the additional cost of fraudulent and exaggerated whiplash claims adds a considerable burden across the entire motor premium. However, the same insurers sell their ‘third party data capt</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ure to ‘list brokers’ and Claims Management Companies (CMC’s). This selling and use of data encourages a whole industry to buy, se</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l, manipulate and encourage ‘cold calling’ to capture claimants. There are a number of regulators involved in this ‘back offi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ce’ hidden market – The F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A, The Data Protection, The CMC regulator and the MoJ. We would encourage that these regulators all review the flow of data in the back office market and see what can be done to tighten up such practices, which damage the reputati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on of legal firms.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Finally for this section we welcome the Government’s encouragement of the insurance industry to share the data held on the Insurance Fraud Register with claimant lawyers. This makes sense on every level and quite frankly would greatly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">enhance the efficiency</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of our operations when giving consideration to the validity of a claim. As a law firm operating on a no win no fee principle there is a significant cost to us in progressing any case that turns out to be flawed. Any means of improvin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g our ability to spot a claimant with a track record of deceit is welcome. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Small Claims Track Threshold</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We welcome the Government’s conclusion that it is not the right time to raise the Small Claims limit. The proposed changes to Small Claims would have significantly limited the access to justice for claimants who are genuinely injured. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are therefore keen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to see that any plans to extend</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the Small Claims Track are further consulted on before </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or if at all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">being introduced. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-