mily:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of the 1,003 UK drivers surv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ey</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed who ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d suffered a road traffic accident 61% estimated their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">compensation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> worth less than £5,000. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As this reform is further considered we would suggest a fairer approach would be to apply a relevant inflationary adjustment to the £1,000 limit from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an agre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed time frame</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, with a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> start point and an ongoing annual increase. This would be a transparent and simple measure to keep claims and costs in step. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The whiplash issue and data sharing</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The need for greater data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> sharing between the insurance and legal industries underlies many of the ambiguities that have been allowed to develop. These have subsequently been used by certain media and policy advocates to unduly influence the prism of scrutiny, in doing so they hav</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e exploited the wider debate around reform of the compensation system following an injury in a road traffic accident to their own ends. Full and proper sharing of data would significantly reduce the ability of any one </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">participant in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the debate from support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing their case for reform with misrepresentative facts. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For example, during the Westminster Hall debate, which took place on Thursday 7 November 2013 to discuss the Committee’s last report, a comparison</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> was made of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the number of reported road traffic acci</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dents that had taken place over the last six years and the rise in the number of personal injury claims. The statistics for reported road traffic accidents come from the Police who must have had the accident reported to them. There is no breakdown of the n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">umber of people in a vehicle or how many unreported accidents lead to a personal injury claim. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In addition, the data has differing time limits, an accident this year and a claim this year may not correlate due to the fact the claim relates to an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">accident</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">u</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">p to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> three years before (statute of limitation) and therefore there is not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">necessarily</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a direct correlation in the data. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">These statistics must be held by the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">claimants’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> insurance provider and we would argue that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">data does not provide competitive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">advanta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ge the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> current reluctance of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">corporate players to share this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> must be overcome</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We accept the Government decision not to wait until definitive and robust data on international comparisons is available, though do not think progressing such a report shou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ld be dropped. We would, however, remind the Committee that if </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">95% of traffic accidents lead to injury any international league table of whiplash claims becomes irrelevant, or at least a reflection of each nation’s legal standards and the effectiveness of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">their compensation processes. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As such the Government’s label of the UK as the ‘Whiplash capital of the world’ must be dropped, it does nothing to help preserve justice while stamping out exaggerated and fraudulent claims. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We welcome the Government’s invit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ation to the insurance industry and its representative bodies to collect information on case volumes, case injury types, initial claim values and final case settlements</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, such information </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">very </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">beneficial</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">we hope you too will push for the public</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ation of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would suggest </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Committee further stress the value of this information to all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">participants</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the personal injury compensation process. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Assessment of costs and benefits of the reforms</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At Your Legal Friend and indeed any other Solicitor firm that undertakes a ‘No Win- No Fee’ case, all costs surrounding the case are borne by the firm. This includes any and all marketing costs, administration and regulatory/statutory documents to and from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> clients on-boarding and the cost of securing and providing a medical assessment. If at the end of the medical assessment the case is not continued for whatever reason, these costs remain the liability of the firm.  It is worth pointing out that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in no </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fee Solicitor firms have both risk, and a strong negative cash flow in managing these cases. It is why a fraudulent or rejected exaggerated case is NOT in the interest of Solicitor firms</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Once a medical assessment has been completed and there is clear evid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ence of injury and loss, then there is potential for interim payments of costs by defendants.  Introducing a clear policy that all claims must have a medical assessment prior to settlement does not necessarily impact on costs for defendants and insurance p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">remiums. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We believe it is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">important</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that the costs of a medical report </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are not taken</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> from genuine </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">victims;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this is an essential criteria to maintaining </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">access to justice. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is one of the mainstays of providing an independent assessment of the client’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> injuries and case for claim. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The cost of a medical report may put</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> off</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a genuine claimant from coming forward, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and asking a claimant that is already in financial distress for a medical assessment payment would deny many genuine claimants a fair process. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Allowing an offer to be made to a claimant ahead of a medical report, regardless of the economic argument will not filter out insincere claimants who may be exaggerating or acting fraudulently.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Your Legal Friend currently insists on a bespoke medical </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">asse</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ssment before taking on a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">claimant’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> case. We ask the medical experts to produce reports that are beyond the average report</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">his means a bespoke</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> report that not only properly informs the lawyer and insurer but</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> should the case go to court</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is readily unde</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rstood by the judge. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It also shows that the claimant has been properly assessed and interviewed, symptoms discussed and noted.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are aware of judges criticising computer generated reports for being unclear and inaccessible</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> lacking the personal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Doctor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-to-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Patient interface</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The costs of these reports are usually met by the defendant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as part of the overall claim (see 32 above)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As the Government develop the structure of an independent medical panel it is important that it focuses on enabling the medical professional to carry out individual assessments as the most effective, and indeed practical, means of determining the validity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and extent of an individual’s injury and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that the panel structure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">does not create an inflexible ‘box ticking’ process.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We remain concerned that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should the small claims limit raise to £5,000 the mainstream litigant in ‘no fault’ claims would face a broad de</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nial of ‘access to justice’.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is clear that greater data sharing will improve </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> industry’s knowledge and understanding of fraud and exaggerated claims </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as well as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> develop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a broader public understanding of whiplash as an injury.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The Government should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be encouraged to make this h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">appen sooner rather than later.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Your Legal Friend remains committed to the reform process and would welcome every opportunity to participate and contribute to the policy process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> through engagement with both the Transport Select </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Committee and the Ministry of Justice. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The full ComRes report </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">UK Road Traffic Accidents: ‘A driver’s view’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> can be accessed </span><a href="http://www.comres.co.uk/poll/1044/your-legal-friend-road-traffic-accidents.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">here</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>